snippet.textDisplay:
this coronavirus being a 'plague' or even SARS is a lot of hyperbole if it doesn't drastically mutate beyond RNA norms. even SARS which killed nearly 1 in 10 basically never mutated (16 sequences and below RNA norms). and the main risk is this new coronavirus is pneumonia -- very rarely a mortal risk to healthy people.

that's not to say that tens of thousands of people getting pneumonia is not a major global health concern -- pneumonia is incredibly deadly to seniors or those with pre-existing conditions. But pneumonia isn't going to kill as many people as SARS. And after its mutation to infect humans, neither coronavirus likely would change much ... for this coronavirus to be as deadly as SARS even, it would need to mutate at an unusually high rate for an RNA -- and to be more deadly than SARS, mutate an almost unheard of rate.

risk of course is containment. If it stays years, then it may mutate enough to be much more deadly. That's why virus do deadly in the past. But we understand containment a lot better now.
